 style, for the world of Indian classical music. Just as in many early forms of Western classical music and the ongoing tradition of jazz, improvisation on a theme or scaleâ€”or, in this case, a ragaâ€”is where the discipline of training meets artistry in the moment. Joining Raghuram to set his harmonic and rhythmic world in motion will be B.U. Ganesh Prasad on the violin and Neyveli Narayanan on the mridangam.','',10,'Show','Fowler Hall','','2013-09-05 19:30:00','2013-11-10 08:00:00','2013-11-10 14:00:00','cvn.thestudentusheringclub@gmail.com','\0','\0',5,0),(304,'Yo-Yo Ma and Kathryn Stott','Cello virtuoso Yo-Yo Maâ€™s masterful, multifaceted career is a testament to his continual search for innovative ways to communicate, and connect, with new audiences. From his base in the classical canon, Maâ€™s journeys from minimalism to McFerrin, from Baroque to bluegrass, and more have yielded more than 75 albums, more than 15 GrammysÂ®, and status as one of the worldâ€™s best-selling recording artists. Additionally, Ma has performed for eight U.S. presidents, serves as a United Nations Messenger of Peace, and has received such prestigious awards as the Avery Fisher Prize, the National Medal of the Arts, and Kennedy Center Honors. Joining Ma for this extraordinary Purdue performance is Kathryn Stott, his collaborator of nearly 30 years and one of Britainâ€™s most versatile, imaginative pianists. Hailed by The Washington Post as â€œevery bit Maâ€™s equal, playingâ€¦with striking individuality.â€ Stott, a versatile performer of standard repertoire as well as new music, is also a remarkable exponent of tango and other Latin dance music, reflected in her collaboration with Ma and leading South American musicians on the GrammyÂ®-winning album Soul of the Tango. Together, the duo will perform a program featuring Manuel de Falla, Heitor Villa-Lobos, Johannes Brahms, and more. Seize this rare opportunity to hear two of our timeâ€™s greatest musicians performing together!\r\n\r\n'