/patrons to take their seat after their question is answered, etc.) Report onsite to Kathy Dietz (426-1223) or Hall of Music house manager.',20,'Show','Fowler Hall','','2014-09-16 11:44:00','2014-09-18 13:00:00','2014-09-18 11:30:00','jamesbritton@purdue.edu','\0','\0',6,0),(377,'Sam Allen with President Daniels','Daniels and Deere & Co. CEO â€“ and Purdue alumnus â€“ Sam Allen will discuss meeting the needs of a growing population. Experts estimate the worldâ€™s population will exceed 9.5 billion by 2050. How can we help provide food, clothing, shelter and infrastructure for that many people while also conserving land and water? John Deere is developing solutions that draw on superior technology and engineering as well as more than 175 years of experience. Every day, John Deere employees seek new and better ways to achieve the companyâ€™s higher purpose of helping people live better lives through its commitment to those linked to the land. Students must bring IDs for class credit. - See more at: http://www.convocations.org/presidentiallectureseries/#sthash.u73COzQ9.dpuf','Details: (2) CVNs; call time 1:45 pm; release approx. 3:35 pm\r\nÂ·        Responsibilities: assist at doors with student ID scanning (CCO will provide scanners/laptop and an advisor/technician, line IS NOT exclusively students only); monitor doors for latecomers until approx.. 2:45 pm (Hall of Music will have a house manager onsite); move to the house microphones during the latter part of the Sam Allen event and serve as house ushers (help form a line as students/patrons approach the mics during Q&A, motion for students/patrons to take their seat after their question is answered, etc.) Report onsite to Kathy Dietz (426-1223) or Hall of Music house manager.',20,'Show','Loeb Playhouse','','2014-09-24 17:00:00','2014-09-29 15:35:00','2014-09-29 13:45:00','cvn2@purdue.edu','\0','\0',6,0),(378,'Donald Sinta Quartet','The influence of a mentor can be life-changing. Itâ€™s bigger than the sum of learning, responding, and emulating. Itâ€™s about finding, channeling, and directing oneâ€™s own purposeâ€”but with the momentum of an energy that has been given shape. This is what drives the Donald Sinta Quartet, a saxophone ensemble founded in 2010 and named for the man under whom its members studiedâ€” a legendary performer and University of Michigan professor who has influenced the American articulation of saxophone style and sound for 40 years. This internationally renowned quartet adopted Sintaâ€™s name because they embody his missionâ€”embracing classic repertoire while championing audacious new works and educating the next generation of players. Under his guiding spirit, they won the top prize in the 2013 Concert Artists Guild Victor Elmaleh Competition and have already chalked up concert engagements in China, France, Greece, and Scotland, all while actively commissioning new works that suit their protean technique and gifted artistic sensibilities. Their Purdue engagement will present a robust collection of new music, commissioned works, and transcriptions while also giving voice to celebrated landmarks of saxophone quartet literature.','',10,'Show','Loeb Playhouse','','2014-09-25 15:37:00','2014-10-30 13:30:00','2014-10-30 18:30:00','sgokhal@purdue.edu','\0','\0',6,0),(379,'Brian Greene','Greeneâ€™s national bestseller The Elegant Universe, which recounts the theories of general relativity and quantum mechanics, transformed our understanding of the universe and introduced string theory, a concept that might be the key to a unified theory of the universe. The book sold over a million copies and became an EmmyTM- and PeabodyTM Award-winning Nova special that Greene hosted. His second book, The Fabric of the Cosmos, spent six months on The New York Times Best Seller list and was adapted into a Nova miniseries on PBS. Greeneâ€™s latest bestseller, The Hidden Reality: Parallel Universes and the Deep Laws of the Cosmos, was published in January 2011.\r\n\r\nWorking to bring scientific knowledge to the masses, Greene co-founded the World Science Festival in 2008 and this year launched World Science U, a series of free online courses.\r\n\r\nA Harvard graduate and a Rhodes Scholar at Oxford, Greene is a professor in physics and mathematics at Columbia University. His work has been published in Wired and The New York Times, and he appeared as himself in a 2011 episode of CBSâ€™s The Big Bang Theory. He has also been a guest on Charlie Rose, Nightline, Late Show with David Letterman, and The Colbert Report.','',10,'Show','Elliot Hall of Music','','2014-09-25 15:40:00','2014-11-06 13:00:00','2014-11-06 17:45:00','cvn2@purdue.edu','\0','\0',6,0),(380,'BÃ©la Fleck and Brooklyn Rider','Critics have made a fair amount of fuss over classical musicâ€™s recent appropriation of musical and emotional reference points from rock, pop, and electronic music. Is this novel or, to dare a rhetorical barb, legitimate? How about a more historically informed question: Isnâ€™t this expected? Nearly all celebrated composers in the Western classical canon contemplated other styles within their worksâ€”a natural byproduct of the curiosity that inspires composers and those who perform their music.\r\n\r\nIn this light, itâ€™s no surprise 13-time GrammyÂ®-winning artist BÃ©la Fleck has added classical-music composition and performance to a four decade-long journey of bluegrass, rock, jazz, pop, and world music. Similarly, musical adventurers Brooklyn Rider continue to radically redefine chamber music for the 21st century, with Philip Glass and indie-rock band The National among the groupâ€™s collaborators. This concert unites them for a program anchored by Fleckâ€™s Night Flight Over Waterâ€”a suspenseful chase story that maintains mystery and momentum across three riveting movements for banjo and string quartet. This free-ranging investigation of musical influences will continue in works from Brooklyn Riderâ€™s versatile repertoire, virtuoso solo turns from Fleck, and one-of-a-kind collaborative surprises.','',10,'Show','Loeb Playhouse','','2014-09-25 15:43:00','2014-11-14 14:00:00','2014-11-14 19:00:00','cvn2@purdue.edu','\0','\0',6,0),(381,'Yo-Yo Ma & Katherine Scott','Cello virtuoso Yo-Yo Maâ€™s masterful, multifaceted career is a testament to his continual search for innovative ways to communicate, and connect, with new audiences. From his base in the classical canon, Maâ€™s journeys from minimalism to McFerrin, from Baroque to bluegrass, and more have yielded more than 75 albums, more than 15 GrammysÂ®, and status as one of the worldâ€™s best-selling recording artists. Additionally, Ma has performed for eight U.S. presidents, serves as a United Nations Messenger of Peace, and has received such prestigious awards as the Avery Fisher Prize, the National Medal of the Arts, and Kennedy Center Honors. Joining Ma for this extraordinary Purdue performance is Kathryn Stott, his collaborator of nearly 30 years and one of Britainâ€™s most versatile, imaginative pianists, hailed by The Washington Post as â€œevery bit Maâ€™s equal, playingâ€¦with striking individuality.â€ Stott, a versatile performer of standard repertoire as well as new music, is also a remarkable exponent of tango and other Latin dance music, reflected in her collaboration with Ma and leading South American musicians on the GrammyÂ®-winning album Soul of the Tango. Together, the duo will perform a program featuring Manuel de Falla, Heitor Villa-Lobos, Johannes Brahms, and more.','Yo-Yo Ma visited us last year, but was unable to perform due to a weather emergency. Tickets for this show are sold out, so ushering is the only way to see it. ',10,'Show','Loeb Playhouse','','2014-09-25 15:46:00','2014-10-15 13:30:00','2014-10-15 18:30:00','reed83@purdue.edu','\0','\0',6,0),(382,'Flat Stanley (Pre-Show)','Assist visiting kids in creating Flat Stanley cutouts to take home','',10,'Show','Loeb Playhouse','','2014-09-25 15:51:00','2014-11-16 08:00:00','2014-11-16 13